==== Condenser (capacitor) Microphones
\n
Condenser microphones use a {capacitor:link} (an older word is condenser) for transducing acoustic energy into electrical energy. A capacitor consists of two plates with an insulator in between them. The capacitance of a capacitor depends on the size of the plates and the distance between them.

{diagram, capacitor}
{diagram, capacitor microphone}

The schematic above shows that a condenser microphone has two plates, one of which is the membrane and the other one the so-called back-plate. If we measured the capacitance of a fully charged capacitor it would remain constant unless we change the distance between the plates or their sizes. As of now, microphones do not yet magically change in size it is unlikely that the size of the plates will change, so we can assume that they remain constant. When sound waves reach the membrane (which is very thin and light), the membrane starts to move back and forth following the changes in air pressure. We will take a closer look at how it moves in the section on {link_acoustic operating principles}. When the membrane moves and the fixed back-plate does not, the distance between the plates changes. Thus, the capacitance changes.

