==== Phantom Power
\n
{change, move section below dynamic microphones}
The capacitor needs to be charged before the microphone can operate, which is usually done with so-called {/phantom power}. This power is provided by the device the microphone is connected to (e.g., mixing console or interface) and the most common voltage that is in use is 48V. However, there are other voltages out there as well. When using phantom power always make sure to apply the amount of voltage the microphone is expecting and only give it to those microphones that need it. In addition, do not connect or disconnect microphones while it is supplied with phantom power. Connect the microphones first then give it phantom power or turn off the power and then un-plug the microphone. You should also not cross-patch microphones on a patchbay while


==== Dynamic Microphones
\n
{*Moving Coil Microphone}
\n
When you move a conductor through a magnetic field a current starts flowing through the conductor ({link, induction}). The amount of current depends on the strength of the magnetic field, the length of the conductor inside the magnetic field and the velocity of its movement. This behaviour can be used to transduce air pressure changes into voltage changes. To do so we attach a membrane to a coil so that the coil starts moving when the membrane moves. Then we place the coil inside a magnetic field of a strong magnet. A coil is used to have as much length of wire inside the magnetic field as possible which gives you the most output. When air pressure changes move the membrane it moves the coil inside the magnetic field which induces a current that is proportional to the pressure changes of the incoming sound wave.

