{*Ribbon Microphone}
\n
A ribbon microphone works very similar to the moving coil microphone, just that the membrane and the coil are replaced by a thin ribbon that is placed directly inside the magnetic field. Because the ribbon is a lot lighter than the coil, ribbon microphones can react very quickly and thus usually have an excellent transient response.
\n
{diagram, show difference in transient response between moving coil and ribbon microphone, would it be possible to give the user the option to change the mass and investigate how that would influence the transient?}
\n
However because of the thin ribbon they are also a lot more fragile than moving coil microphones. Especially some vintage ribbons can easily break or be damaged when exposed to high sound pressure levels or when supplied with phantom power. So always keep in mind that dynamic microphones do not need phantom power because there is no capacitor that needs to be charged and the magnet that is used for the transduction is charged permanently. While most moving coil dynamic microphones probably do not mind the phantom power, ribbon microphones could be damanged as soon as you feed them with 48V, so be very careful when working with dynamic and condenser microphones within the same session. As always, there are some exceptions to this. For example, the Royer R122 actually needs phantom power to operate. Just like cross patching with active phantom power can damage your condenser microphones, it is also likely going to damage those ribbon microphones that have not yet been destroyed by the phantom power itself. If in doubt, read the manual of the microphones you are intending to use.
 
